responses.response: It’s four years of studying and all-nighters. Your classmates go out and enjoy their last years at home. You don’t care. You have dreams to build.
It’s all so tedious. Performative. Fake smiles, handshakes, student clubs. You win HS DECA awards for being a visionary. Does that even matter?
It’s a sharp pivot. You alternate between long stretches of laziness, chaotic underage parties, and frenetic bouts of catching up to schoolwork. The American Dream.

Driving by the barren fields that surround the campuses of UW-Madison, UIUC, and Michigan, you can’t help but wonder if you made a bad choice. Nevertheless, you’re accepted into Purdue and decide to commit.

Ivy day rolls around, and you’re rejected from seven of them. You can picture them laughing at your pitiful essays. The only one with good news? Cornell. Sure, it’s not MIT, but at least you’re not at Rutgers or UMass Amherst.

The sun-kissed valleys of the Bay and the picturesque beaches of SoCal are to die for. You’re rejected from all 8 of the UCs and CSUs you applied to. Stanford probably didn’t even open your folder. Your saving grace is the rainy University of Washington in Seattle.

You quickly realize that for every Vanderbilt and Duke, there’s a dozen more LSUs academically. You’re puzzled by the presence of Confederate statues in the same town that hosts NASA Marshall. In the end, you end up committing to Georgia Tech.

When the applause finally dies down, you look down at the people clapping and wonder how many of them will peak here. Either way, there’s no time to care about dead weight. It’s time for a new chapter in your life.

While everyone’s out there enjoying new friends and exploring campus, you look like a maniac measuring the time it takes to walk between academic halls. But hey, maybe the 4.0 GPA will make it worthwhile.

Sips turn into shots, which turn into swigs. Your stomach hates you and your brain is in revolt. You can’t help but wonder how much you’ve changed from High School, and what people would think about you now.

What was supposed to be a productive session of organization and unpacking quickly devolved into an afternoon of bedrotting. Every time you scroll to another TikTok, you can picture more synapses withering and dying.
Your optimistic best friend decides to go alone. She comes back with an interview scheduled at UPS for a Data Analytics role. You stare at your empty inbox in silence.
You think it’s an avenue to explore, but you quickly realize it’s just mailing list fluff. The same day, your charismatic roommate connects with an AMD recruiter online.
You could feel the pity. Quite frankly, you should’ve known better, but they silently respect the balls you had to go up to Lockheed Martin and Stratasys as a freshman.

After the fair, there’s lots of new faces looking to “make an impact.” But the rest of the club rightfully sees you all as carpetbaggers desperate for a ladder out of the pit. Either way, you have work to do.

A case and behavioral interview later, you’re officially in the frat. It’s a nice couple of days before you realize that it (like any business-adjacent club) is a nothingburger. At least you’ll learn Excel.
It’s 3 AM. You’ve been staring at a LeetCode Hard for the past 90 minutes. Your roommate kicked you out of the room to bring a girl over. You fight back the soreness in your eyes.
You fire off a strongly worded group chat message at 10:00 AM. They all read it. No one replies. You notice their commits being pushed to the repo later that evening.
Two people cancel, one shows up late. After a lengthy discussion about accountability and norms, no concrete agreement is made. Still, it’s progress, and they appreciate you trying.
Your TA checks the group repo and notes that 80% of the codebase has been written by you alone. You notice the same thing while buying another case of Red Bull.

You show up in the nick of time. Plug in the laptop. When the questions come, you’re sharp. Relaxed. In control. Well-rested. Your team daps you up after. Pure and deserved bliss.
You send a text: “Sorry, something came up.” They reply, “Ok.” Nothing more. You sleep through the morning. It helps for a bit. But when you wake up, the shame’s already waiting for you.

You stare the therapist in the eyes for 90 minutes.  Does she even understand what pressure you’re under? Does she really believe in you? Isn’t she just paid to keep you happy? Either way, it works.
Your next battery of midterms yields dramatically better results. At the same time, your daily dosage of caffeine creeps upward while your average length of sleep steadily declines.

You’re now considered a regular among the party scene. The night swiftly turns into a blur, but all you know is that it was a needed reprieve. Your roommate spots you drinking with the same girl all night long.

You bond with classmates over copious amounts of beer while playing MarioKart. A cute girl is there and you exchange Instagrams. Your best friend sees it and silently immortalizes the blackmail in her mind.
Your home team gets routed off the field 52-21. The commentators call it an absolute disgrace, but you pay no mind. It’s a blast getting to make new friends there.
She asks if you’re okay. You fight back the welling tears. You’re stronger than this. You’re meant to be here. It’s just another setback, you say.

Despite your own protests, your friends force you to go home for the break. You sit at the end of the dinner table, listening to your Woke mom and MAGA uncle scream their heads off. There’s no place like home.

You preach about user privacy, design systems, and your hatred of Material UI to the Apple booth. The recruiter listens quietly, then asks if you’d be willing to relocate to Cupertino.

You nod so hard your iPhone drops. The offer to interview comes before you’ve even opened LinkedIn.

You walk away in a daze, convinced you just won the lottery.

You speak in fluent acronyms—MMFs, HFT, QE. You talk about rates with the detached violence of someone who actually reads central bank PDFs.

The Jane Street recruiter doesn’t smile. She just scribbles your name down and tells you to be ready by Tuesday.

You feel like you passed a test no one told you existed.

You speak with reverence about aerospace telemetry and fifth-gen RAM coatings. The Lockheed Martin recruiter hits you with acronyms that sound like classified documents. You respond in kind.

There’s a brief pause. Then she nods. “You’ll do.”

You don’t remember the rest of the fair—you were too busy mentally rehearsing your Top Secret clearance interview.

You mention topology optimization and polymer blends in the same sentence. The Stratasys recruiter doesn’t blink. She asks if you’ve ever worked with a Markforged.

You say yes, even though you haven't. Doesn’t matter—you’re invited to the next round.

You pretend not to notice your hands shaking with excitement.

The Amazon recruiter gives you a thin smile. Hands you a QR code. “Apply online,” she says. She turns around and greets your roommate behind you with their name. 

You stand there, blinking. At least Deloitte still wants you.

You launch into a pitch about economic resilience, embedded payments, and your fascination with policy-driven FinTech innovation. The recruiter blinks once, nods twice, and pulls you aside for a talk. You don’t even remember what you said, but you sail past first round either way.

You say “machine learning” and “financial accessibility” like you just read it off a slide. She asks you a question about the Fed’s role in stimulus. You blink. “Apply online,” she says, turning to complement your best friend’s blazer.

You stare at your resume, unsure what it even says. Deloitte it is.

You shamble up to their booth and ramble on and on about their work on the F-35’s avionics suite. They’re just university recruiters. Neither you nor they actually understand the conversation that takes place, but it’s enough to get you to finals.

You say “defense” with the enthusiasm of someone who just Googled what L3Harris does. You mumble something about “military-adjacent tech.” She replies, “we’ll be in touch.” The Deloitte recruiter catches your eye from across the room. You know what’s coming.

You drop a line about AI ethics and quantum computing, and their ears perk up. A recruiter asks about your thoughts on hybrid cloud strategies, and you rattle off something about Red Hat you vaguely remember from Hacker News. They nod, impressed.

You say “cloud computing” like it’s a spell. The recruiter’s smile doesn’t quite reach her eyes. She hands you a flyer and says you’ll “find plenty of great resources online.” You nod, defeated, as the Deloitte recruiter waves you over with a lanyard.

You talk about embedded systems and supply chain resilience. The recruiter looks like they’ve finally found someone who doesn’t flinch at the word 'MES.' You're ushered into a follow-up round almost immediately.

You try to spin your summer of Python tutorials into “strong embedded systems experience.” She thanks you for stopping by and gestures toward the QR code taped to the table. You notice the Deloitte recruiter waving at you.

You gambled little and gained even less. While your friends are locking in offers at Northrop Grumman and Meta, you’re able to beat a bunch of Econ and Finance majors for a Technology Consulting final round.

You hole up in the library, fueled by iced coffee and trauma. The hours blur. By sunrise, your code compiles, your deck looks decent, and your notes are color-coded. Caffeine, a color-coded Notion, and adrenaline pushes you past the finish line this one last time. 

And it’s just enough to punch your ticket on the Dean’s List.
